                    <section id="getting-started">
                        <h2>Getting Started</h2>
                        <p>This infrastructure is deployed using Terraform for provisioning and Ansible for configuration management. The entire stack is reproducible, version-controlled, and automated through GitHub Actions.</p>

                        <h3>Quick Start</h3>
                        <p>Deploy the complete infrastructure with these commands:</p>
                        <div class="docs-pre-wrap">
                            <pre><code># Clone the repository
git clone https://github.com/your-org/secure-aws-infrastructure.git
cd secure-aws-infrastructure

# Bootstrap S3 state backend + DynamoDB lock table
./scripts/bootstrap.sh --bucket your-state-bucket --region us-east-1

# Deploy infrastructure
cd terraform
terraform init
terraform plan
terraform apply

# Configure servers via SSM (no SSH needed)
cd ../ansible
ansible-playbook playbooks/webserver.yml</code></pre>
                        </div>
                        <div class="callout callout-info">
                            <strong>Tip:</strong> The full deploy runs automatically on every merge to <code>main</code> via GitHub Actions. Manual runs are only needed for bootstrapping or out-of-band changes.
                        </div>
                    </section>

                    <section id="prerequisites">
                        <h2>Prerequisites</h2>
                        <p>Ensure the following tools are installed and configured before deploying:</p>
                        <ul>
                            <li>AWS Account with <code>AdministratorAccess</code> or an equivalent custom policy</li>
                            <li>AWS CLI v2.x — configured via <code>aws configure</code> or environment variables</li>
                            <li>Terraform v1.7 or higher</li>
                            <li>Ansible v2.14 or higher</li>
                            <li>Python 3.8+ (required by Ansible)</li>
                        </ul>

                        <h3>AWS Credentials</h3>
                        <div class="docs-pre-wrap">
                            <pre><code># Interactive setup
aws configure

# Or export directly
export AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID="your-access-key"
export AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY="your-secret-key"
export AWS_REGION="us-east-1"

# Verify identity
aws sts get-caller-identity</code></pre>
                        </div>
                    </section>

                    <section id="deployment">
                        <h2>Deployment</h2>

                        <h3>Terraform Modules</h3>
                        <p>The configuration is split into focused, reusable modules:</p>
                        <ul>
                            <li><code>vpc/</code> — Virtual Private Cloud with public/private subnets and routing tables</li>
                            <li><code>alb_asg/</code> — Application Load Balancer and Auto Scaling Group</li>
                            <li><code>ecs_ghost/</code> — ECS Fargate service running Ghost CMS</li>
                            <li><code>rds_mysql/</code> — RDS MySQL with Multi-AZ and automated backups</li>
                            <li><code>monitoring/</code> — CloudWatch dashboards, alarms, and SNS topics</li>
                            <li><code>observability/</code> — Prometheus + Grafana stack</li>
                            <li><code>oidc_role/</code> — GitHub Actions OIDC role for keyless CI/CD</li>
                        </ul>

                        <h3>Ansible Playbooks</h3>
                        <p>After Terraform provisions infrastructure, Ansible configures instances via AWS SSM — no SSH or open ports required:</p>
                        <div class="docs-pre-wrap">
                            <pre><code># Verify SSM connectivity to instances
aws ssm describe-instance-information \
  --query 'InstanceInformationList[*].[InstanceId,PingStatus]' \
  --output table

# Deploy web server (nginx + static files)
ansible-playbook playbooks/webserver.yml -e app_environment=prod

# Configure Ghost database
ansible-playbook playbooks/ghost_db.yml -e app_environment=prod</code></pre>
                        </div>
                    </section>

                    <section id="configuration">
                        <h2>Configuration</h2>

                        <h3>Terraform Variables</h3>
                        <p>Edit <code>terraform/terraform.tfvars</code> to customise your deployment:</p>
                        <div class="docs-pre-wrap">
                            <pre><code># General
environment           = "production"
aws_region            = "us-east-1"

# Networking
vpc_cidr              = "10.0.0.0/16"
public_subnet_count   = 2
private_subnet_count  = 2

# Compute
instance_type         = "t3.micro"
min_size              = 1
max_size              = 4

# Monitoring
cpu_threshold         = 80
memory_threshold      = 80
alarm_email_endpoints = ["alerts@example.com"]</code></pre>
                        </div>

                        <h3>Ansible Variables</h3>
                        <p>Web server settings live at the top of <code>playbooks/webserver.yml</code>:</p>
                        <div class="docs-pre-wrap">
                            <pre><code>vars:
  aws_region:    "us-east-1"
  deploy_env:    "{{ '{{' }} app_environment | default('prod') {{ '}}' }}"
  app_directory: /var/www/html
  nginx_port:    80
  company_name:  "ClaudiQ"</code></pre>
                        </div>
                        <div class="callout callout-warn">
                            <strong>Security:</strong> Sensitive values (RDS passwords, API keys) must be stored in AWS Secrets Manager or passed as GitHub Secrets — never committed to the repository.
                        </div>
                    </section>

                    <section id="monitoring">
                        <h2>Monitoring</h2>

                        <h3>CloudWatch</h3>
                        <p>Pre-configured dashboards and alarms cover all key metrics:</p>
                        <ul>
                            <li>CPU, Memory, and Disk utilisation on EC2 instances</li>
                            <li>ALB request count, latency (p50/p95/p99), and 5xx error rate</li>
                            <li>RDS connections, read/write IOPS, and free storage</li>
                            <li>ECS task count, container health, and restart frequency</li>
                        </ul>

                        <h3>Grafana</h3>
                        <p>Prometheus metrics are visualised in a self-hosted Grafana instance provisioned by Terraform. Access it at the configured <code>grafana_domain_name</code> output.</p>

                        <h3>Health Endpoints</h3>
                        <div class="docs-pre-wrap">
                            <pre><code># Plain-text health check (used by ALB target group)
curl http://{{ ansible_default_ipv4.address }}/health
# → 200 OK  body: "OK"

# JSON health response with timestamp
curl http://{{ ansible_default_ipv4.address }}/api/health
# → 200 OK  body: {"status":"healthy","timestamp":"2026-03-17T..."}</code></pre>
                        </div>
                    </section>

                    <section id="security">
                        <h2>Security</h2>

                        <h3>Controls Implemented</h3>
                        <ul>
                            <li>VPC isolation — compute and database tiers in private subnets</li>
                            <li>TLS everywhere — ACM certificates, HTTPS redirect on the ALB</li>
                            <li>Encryption at rest — EBS, RDS, and S3 all use AES-256</li>
                            <li>Security groups with least-privilege ingress rules</li>
                            <li>IMDSv2 enforced on all EC2 instances</li>
                            <li>Secrets Manager for all credentials — no plaintext secrets in code</li>
                            <li>VPC Flow Logs shipped to CloudWatch for network auditing</li>
                        </ul>

                        <h3>Security Scanning</h3>
                        <p>Automated scanning runs on every pull request via GitHub Actions:</p>
                        <div class="docs-pre-wrap">
                            <pre><code># Terraform IaC scanning
cd terraform
checkov -d .
tfsec .

# Secret detection
trufflehog git file://. --only-verified

# Ansible linting
ansible-lint ansible/playbooks/</code></pre>
                        </div>
                    </section>

                    <section id="troubleshooting">
                        <h2>Troubleshooting</h2>

                        <h4>Terraform State Lock</h4>
                        <div class="docs-pre-wrap">
                            <pre><code># Inspect the lock record
aws dynamodb get-item --table-name terraform-locks \
  --key '{"LockID":{"S":"your-bucket/terraform.tfstate-md5"}}'

# Force-unlock (use with caution — confirm no active apply)
terraform force-unlock LOCK_ID</code></pre>
                        </div>

                        <h4>SSM Connectivity</h4>
                        <div class="docs-pre-wrap">
                            <pre><code># Check SSM agent status
aws ssm describe-instance-information \
  --filters "Key=InstanceIds,Values=i-xxxx" \
  --query 'InstanceInformationList[0].PingStatus'

# Open an interactive session
aws ssm start-session --target i-xxxx</code></pre>
                        </div>

                        <h4>nginx Not Starting</h4>
                        <div class="docs-pre-wrap">
                            <pre><code># Validate config syntax
nginx -t

# View recent logs
journalctl -u nginx -n 50 --no-pager

# Restart and check status
systemctl restart nginx && systemctl status nginx</code></pre>
                        </div>
                    </section>

                    <section id="api">
                        <h2>API Reference</h2>

                        <h3>Endpoints</h3>

                        <h4>GET /health</h4>
                        <p>Plain-text health check consumed by the ALB target group health check.</p>
                        <div class="docs-pre-wrap">
                            <pre><code>curl http://{{ ansible_default_ipv4.address }}/health
# 200 OK — "OK"</code></pre>
                        </div>

                        <h4>GET /api/health</h4>
                        <p>JSON health response including server timestamp.</p>
                        <div class="docs-pre-wrap">
                            <pre><code>curl http://{{ ansible_default_ipv4.address }}/api/health
# 200 OK — {"status":"healthy","timestamp":"2026-03-17T10:00:00+00:00"}</code></pre>
                        </div>

                        <h4>GET /</h4>
                        <p>Main landing page with live infrastructure details captured at deploy time.</p>

                        <h4>GET /docs</h4>
                        <p>This documentation page.</p>

                        <h3>Response Codes</h3>
                        <ul>
                            <li><code>200 OK</code> — Request successful</li>
                            <li><code>404 Not Found</code> — Resource not found</li>
                            <li><code>500 Internal Server Error</code> — Server error</li>
                            <li><code>503 Service Unavailable</code> — Service temporarily unavailable</li>
                        </ul>
                    </section>

